snippet.textDisplay: Since Rohail Hyatt left ,the program has taken a different trajectory with Strings.The musical arrangement is distinctly different.What remains constant is the fact that if a timeless folk classic is sung well with contemporary arrangement it will  enhance its melody and bring in more youngsters to appreciate the rich traditions of folk music in south asia.Shilpa Rao has actually been magical in the mid segment .Some comments here have suggested that QB might have been better with her powerhouse vocals.I politely disagree.The restraint in the high and long notes are absolutely brilliant in this song,giving it a sophistication and longing that are critical.All in all a great composition put to great contemp arrangement and sung well.

snippet.textDisplay: Undoubtedly, Rohail Hyatt was a best producer for Coke Studio Pakistan and he created wonderful songs. He has credit of creating first Pakistani pop band Vital Signs  (I never heard any song of Vital Signs song, have read them through Rock and Roll Jihad by Salman Ahmad founder of Junoon band) and Junoon. The season 9 of Coke Studio Pakistan is really crap. They have compromised with the quality. It was not what I had expected from the Coke Studio Pakistan. However, in season 9, Noorie did a wonderful job. Aaja re more Saiyan was definitely a master piece. Episode 1 was somewhat good with Aaqa and Aaja re more saiyan. Episode 2 and 3 were highly disappointing. However, they picked up in episode 4 and I loved 2 songs-  Aaya Lariye (traditional rendition) and Paar Chanaa De. I loved Paar Chanaa De due to several reason 1. The song is really nice 2. Shilpa rao collaborated with it and imagine, an Indian singing in a Pakistani Coke studio, a real fusion, a message that both country has border, but culturally they are one. Thats something I wanted to see and the best part is to see Noorie are back in coke studio. Enjoy this wonderful song to make your day and yes, don't forget to watch and listen Aaya Lariye Ni too. #CokeStudio9 long live the music, long live the unity.

snippet.textDisplay:
Listening to Coke Studio Pakistan makes me forget everything. Its just so beautiful.
When the old lady started playing the veena (I guess. Since I am not sure if its veena), I got goosebumps. 
And so happy that our Shilpa got a chance to perform at such an amazing platform with such talented artists. 
And I just loved the voice of the guy at the end. 
God! So good. <3
